column15: The quality of the commercial landings and catch-at-age data for this stock deteriorated in the 1990s following reductions in the TAC without associated control of fishing effort. The WG considers the international landings figures from 1993 onwards to have inaccuracies that lead to retrospective underestimation of fishing mortality and over estimation of spawning stock biomass and other problems with an analytical assessment. The assessment is, however, consistent, despite problems with discards.

column15: The F3-7 (Figure 2.2.7.1.6) seems to be a problematic measure of fishing mortality for two reasons. Firstly, the fishing mortalities for ages 6-7 are generally overestimated in the terminal year leading to an overestimation of F3-7 for the terminal year. Secondly, the proportion of 6-7 year old cod in the stock or catch is small (normally less than 20%) and therefore get a disproportionate influence on the F3-7.

The final assessment presented is based on survey data alone and therefore no F series is available.

The assessment is solely based on surveys. Therefore the time series are presented in relative values, not absolute.
column15: The assessment is considered only to be indicative of stock trends. All time series are relative values (standardized between the surveys). Until revised Scottish discards are available and Irish discards included, an analytic assessment is not possible for this stock. The assessment presented by the WG this year is therefore based only on survey data which is the same approach as that adopted last year. Absolute reference points (provided in the assessment document) have been removed as they cannot be interpreted (ratios etc.) in the context of the current relative assessment

column15: Unreported landings represent a cause for concern between 1994-2005. The 2006 data are assumed more reliable with the introduction of Buyers and Sellers registration. A study by the sea mammal research unit (SMRU) on seal predation has indicated that seal predation on cod probably constitutes significant natural mortality. As such, mortality outputs from the assessment are not considered to represent a fishing mortality F at age for recent years in the time series but rather estimates, (referred to here as Z-0.2), of total mortality that can not be accounted for by the standard value used for natural mortality e.g. seals.

column15: High levels of discarding are known to occur in this fishery as well as potential misreporting. An update ICA assessment has been presented as the final assessment in accordance with the assessment status assigned to this stock prior to the working group. However, the working group has serious reservations regarding the appropriateness of the model fit given the clear trends in catchability residuals evident from the beam trawl survey indices. Given the poor fit of the assessment model, estimates of fishing mortality and stock biomass should be interpreted with caution.

column15: As no recruitment estimates from surveys are available, recruitment estimated in the assessments are based exclusively on commercial catch-at-age data. There is a tendency to underestimate F and overestimate biomas in the assessment, although this is lessened in this year s assessment. No fishing mortality (F) reference points are given for sandeels in the North Sea because there is only a weak correlation between the size of the spawning stock biomass and the recruitment.

column15: The quality of the commercial landings and catch-at-age data for this stock deteriorated in the 1990s following reductions in the TAC without associated control of fishing effort. The WG considers the international landings figures from 1993 onwards to have inaccuracies that lead to retrospective underestimation of fishing mortality and over estimation of spawning stock biomass and other problems with an analytical assessment. The assessment is, however, consistent, despite problems with discards.

This assessment focuses on the inshore component of the 2J3KL cod stock as there is very little data on the offshore component. All data concerns the inshore component only except the total landings and total catch time series which are for both components. There was one SPA model used in this assessment; and it was only run for years 1995-2005. The data for total catch is an age-dissaggregated time series that comes from Table 10 in the assessment. The numbers for total landings are the only ones who include the entire area; both offshore and inshore.

Information on catch and landings can be found in the assessment divided into different tables according to area and type of fishing gear. The two VPA models used ages 4-8 only as ages 2-3 are considered to be non-spawners and ages 9+ are too few in numbers. There is one unknown reference point included in this assessment; it is called "reference value" and it is a biomass of 12 000 metric tons; for more information on this read page 12 of the assessment.

The two VPA models used ages 4-8 only as ages 2-3 are considered to be non-spawners and ages 9+ are too few in numbers. There is one unknown reference point included in this assessment; it is called "reference value" and it is a biomass of 12 000 metric tons; for more information on this read page 12 of the assessment.
